<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 94 / Aitken acts to clear name with hotel letters: Confusion over
payment of bill blamed on an accounting mistake by Ritz
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jonathan Aitken, the treasury chief secretary, last night published
confidential documentation with a view to clearing his name of allegations
that a business associate paid his bill at Mr Mohamed Fayed's Paris Ritz
hotel.
In a statement issued by the treasury, Mr Aitken said that confusion over
his FFr8,010 (Pounds 956.71) bill for a two-night stay at the Ritz was
caused by a mistake by the hotel, rectified five months later.
The statement, accompanied by photostat copies of letters and a cheque for
Pounds 426.88, followed allegations by The Guardian that part of Mr Aitken's
bill was paid by Mr Said Ayas, a former business associate.
Mr Aitken had been cleared of impropriety by Sir Robin Butler, cabinet
secretary, after disclosing that his wife paid half the bill in cash. But
the government had refused to publish documentary evidence said by Sir Robin
to prove that Mr Aitken had paid the bill in full.
Mr Aitken said his bill was drawn up, without his knowledge, in the name of
Mr Ayas. He said his wife was asked to pay FFr4,257 in cash, and several
months later 'when I went over the documents again', it emerged that Mr
Abdul Rahman, another guest whose room was booked by Mr Ayas, had paid
FFr3,753 too much and Mrs Aitken the same amount too little.
Mr Aitken said he sent a cheque for the sterling equivalent (Pounds 426.88),
and a letter of explanation to Mr Rahman. He said the letter, a copy of the
cheque, another letter from the hotel manager and the hotel receipt were
passed to Sir Robin more than six months ago. 'I hope that it is clear that
my bill was paid in full by my wife and myself in the circumstances I have
described, and that I made the full documentation available to the cabinet
secretary, as he has confirmed,' he said.
The cabinet office inquiry was established by the prime minister, Mr John
Major, after an unnamed informant allegedly acting for Mr Fayed made
allegations against a number of ministers. Two, Mr Neil Hamilton and Mr Tim
Smith, later resigned.
Mr Major told the Commons on Tuesday that the intermediary threatened to
publish allegations of ministerial wrongdoing unless a critical DTI report
into Mr Fayed's acquisition of House of Fraser, Harrods parent company, was
withdrawn.
A detailed note of the prime minister's conversation with the intermediary
has been sent to Mrs Barbara Mills, the director of public prosecutions, and
is being investigated by the police.
Mr Aitken's decision to release the evidence supporting his denial of the
allegations followed a further exchange of letters between Sir Robin and Mr
Peter Preston, editor of The Guardian. Sir Robin said the documentation in
his possession was a personal matter for Mr Aitken, suggesting that the
chief secretary was coming under pressure from Downing Street to end
speculation by releasing the evidence.
Mr Aitken won the full backing of his constituency association in Thanet
South last night. But his statement left some questions unanswered:
principally why the balance of the bill was paid five months after the hotel
visit - and after The Guardian began to inquire into the apparent
discrepancy.
Questions about the series of allegations of improprieties dominated the
prime minister's visit to Wales yesterday. He rebuked reporters who
questioned him about Dame Angela Rumbold's decision to resign from a
lobbying firm.
</TEXT>
