<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 94 / International Company News: Claims provisions hit earnings
at Aetna
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Earnings at Aetna, the US insurance group, were hit by further additions to
reserves to meet environmental claims during the third quarter, contributing
to a 25 per cent fall in operating earnings.
The Dollars 23m of extra reserves in the latest period come on top of a
Dollars 64m charge to cover indemnity-related pollution costs taken during
the previous quarter. The earlier provision had shocked investors, and
prompted concern that big environmental-related liabilities might lie buried
at other insurers as well. Hopes that a reform of the US Superfund
environmental clean-up law would ease insurers' liabilities in this area
have been dampened by the Clinton administration's failure to push through
legislation in recent months.
The addition to reserves announced yesterday, although causing less
consternation than the second-quarter charge, contributed to a slight fall
in Aetna's share price during the morning, against the background of a
strongly rising stock market.
Aetna's latest results were also held back by higher catastrophe insurance
losses, as the company added further to its estimate of the cost of the Los
Angeles earthquake at the beginning of the year. Catastrophe losses during
the third quarter were Dollars 28m, Dollars 10m more than the third quarter
of 1993.
These factors, along with capital losses of Dollars 11m compared with gains
of Dollars 13m a year ago, helped to mask an increase in underlying
operating profits in the commercial property/casualty business, from Dollars
48m to Dollars 59. Personal property/casualty profits slipped on higher
reinsurance costs.
Aetna's health and life insurance business, along with financial services,
posted profit gains, while it took net capital losses of Dollars 20m,
compared with gains of Dollars 29m the year before. Overall net income of
Dollars 129m, or Dollars 1.15 a share, was down from Dollars 226m, or
Dollars 2.03 a share.
</TEXT>
