<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 94 / Walker received Pounds 1m in legal aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr George Walker, the leisure entrepreneur cleared of orchestrating a fraud
at Brent Walker, his former company, received more than Pounds 1m in legal
aid it was disclosed yesterday, James Blitz writes.
Mr John Taylor, the parliamentary secretary at the Lord Chancellor's
Department, said Mr Walker, who was acquitted earlier this week, had
received Pounds 1,152,442 to help fight his case.
In a Commons written answer, Mr Taylor said the sum was 'in the form of
discretionary interim payments made in respect of proceedings in the Crown
Court'.
He said it was not possible to estimate, as yet, what the final cost of the
court case would be, although the total sum has been estimated at Pounds 5m.
Mr Walker had been accused of masterminding the fraudulent boost of Brent
Walker's profits by Pounds 19m during the 1980s but was cleared of all
charges of theft, conspiracy and false accounting brought against him by the
Serious Fraud Office.
Mr Taylor also revealed that Mr Ian Maxwell and Mr Kevin Maxwell, the sons
of Robert Maxwell, have already received Pounds 400,000 in legal aid
payments to help fight charges arising out of the collapse of their father's
business empire.
</TEXT>
