<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 94 / US asks UN to lift ban on Bosnia arms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The US last night introduced a UN Security Council resolution calling for a
lifting of the arms embargo against Bosnia in six months unless the Bosnian
Serbs accept an international peace plan.
The resolution also seeks the 'orderly and safe redeployment' of UN
personnel in the Balkans if the embargo is lifted.
The resolution is virtually certain to be defeated because its does not have
the nine votes needed for passage in the 15-member council. Even if it did,
Russia could use its veto.
President Clinton has promised Congress that he will seek a multilateral
decision to lift the arms embargo on the Bosnian government and will
consider lifting it unilaterally if that effort fails. But Mr Clinton
recently said it would be a mistake for Washington to lift the arms ban
unilaterally.
In Bosnia Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Serb leader, yesterday pledged to launch
a massive counter-attack to recover ground lost in a lightning offensive by
the Moslem Bosnian army.
Government forces were consolidating their grip on 80 square miles of
territory in northern Bosnia seized over the past three days.
Referring to this operation, a US state department spokesman said: 'The
Bosnian federation, which represents the principal victims of Serb
aggression, has understandably decided to exercise its right to defend
itself by force of arms.'
Mr David Johnson expressed 'regret that fighting has become necessary, and
that there will be more casualties in an area that has already seen more
than its share of conflict and suffering.' But he stressed that Washington
viewed the Bosnian Serbs as aggressors who had rejected an international
peace plan.
According to UN officials, the Bosnian Serbs - isolated from Belgrade and
facing a growing shortage of fuel - were caught unawares by the latest
onslaught and abandoned armour and equipment as they fled.
Mr Karadzic pledged last night that his forces would 'mount a drive to
encircle, destroy and expel Moslem forces from the territories of Serb
municipalities, using all permitted means.'
In other potentially ominous developments for the Bosnian Serbs, government
forces mounted an assault near the stronghold of Kupres, west of Sarajevo,
and the UN and Nato agreed on new procedures for air strikes.
The new rules allow for air strikes without warning and give greater
discretion - though by no means a free hand - to Nato in the selection of
targets.
The Moslem successes reflect a gradual shift in the balance of military
power inside Bosnia, thanks to clandestine supplies of light arms and the
'over-stretched' condition of the Bosnian-Serb army as it struggles to hold
on to 70 per cent of the republic's territory.
The flare-up in Bosnian fighting coincides with a breakthrough in
international efforts to achieve a broad reconciliation between Serbs and
Croats.
Lord Owen and Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, the mediators on former Yugoslavia,
announced that Zagreb and Belgrade would start regular consultations at
foreign minister level on normalising their relations.
Serbia's President Slobodan Milosevic has been told by western countries and
Russia that he should recognize Croatia as a precondition for further easing
of UN sanctions against his country.
On the face of things, both the Bosnian fighting and the peace moves in
Croatia are part of a single process: the decision by Mr Milosevic to seek
international favour and sever or at least loosen ties with his former
proteges in both neighbouring republics.
Under one scenario, a Belgrade-Zagreb reconciliation would deepen the
Bosnian Serbs' isolation and make them more willing to sue for peace on
acceptable terms.
But few observers see any prospect of the Bosnian partition plan devised by
four western nations and Russia being accepted in its current form.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
