<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / International Bonds: Trans-Tokyo Bay offer sees strong
demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN BRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The euromarkets saw a paucity of issues yesterday as borrowers stood on the
sidelines awaiting the reaction to today's figures on GDP from the US.
The main deal of the day was Trans-Tokyo Bay Highway Corp, which brought a
Dollars 200m, 10-year deal with a 8 3/8 per cent coupon via Bank of Tokyo
Capital Markets.
A syndicate manager said demand for the deal was far stronger than expected.
'This is a hot issue,' he said, with sales to institutions in Asia and
Europe.
Yesterday's deal came at 38 basis points over the comparable Treasury, and
did not move when freed to trade, said BoT. Other syndicates said the deal
was fairly priced.
Bayerische Hypobank brought a ADollars 75m, three-year deal with a 9 3/4 per
cent coupon which lead-manager Hambros said met retail demand in Europe.
This was Hambros' 31st deal this year in the Australian dollar sector, and
Bayerische Hypobank's second. Its first deal came in August with an 8 3/4
per cent coupon and by yesterday had tightened in by 35 basis points, said
Hambros.
Deutsche Bank Finance brought a Dollars 200m deal with a 7.5 per cent coupon
and a 39-month maturity. There was an excellent response from other
syndicates, said lead manager Deutsche Bank, which brought this deal after
seeing good demand for the three-year tranche of the Johnson &amp; Johnson deal
this week.
Dresdner International Finance opted for ABN-Amro Bank to handle its first
visit this year to the euromarkets with a Fl 250m, five-year offer.
</TEXT>
