<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / International Company News: Canadian Airlines posts record
earnings for term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Canadian Airlines Inter-national, which was on the brink of collapse before
the conclusion of a financial restructuring earlier this year, has bounced
back with record quarterly earnings.
The Calgary-based airline will take another important step forward next week
when it implements a wide-ranging services contract with AMR Corp, the
holding company of American Airlines. AMR paid CDollars 246m (USDollars
182m) for a 25 per cent voting interest in the Canadian carrier as part of
the restructuring.
The contract, which is valued at about USDollars 110m a year, includes a
switch to AMR's data-processing and yield-management facilities and to its
Sabre computer-reservation system.
PWA Corp, Canadian's holding company, reported third-quarter earnings of
CDollars 85.4m, or 11 cents a share, up from CDollars 38.5m, or 78 cents.
The latest per-share figure reflects a significant dilution as a result of a
big debt-to-equity conversion which formed part of the restructuring, and
which cut interest expense.
Nine-month net profit was CDollars 19.5m, against a loss of CDollars 199m a
year earlier, including special charges. Operating income climbed by 8.3 per
cent to CDollars 110.6m, due to increased traffic and an improved yield per
mile. The load factor was unchanged at 76.8 per cent.
Mr Drew Fitch, senior vice-president for finance, said the airline aims to
achieve earnings of CDollars 75m next year, and cash flow from operations of
CDollars 500m by 1997.
AMR's 20-year contract with Canadian reflects the US carrier's efforts to
expand the services which it provides to other airlines. The two airlines
are also co-operating in marketing, including reciprocity for their
frequent-flier programmes.
</TEXT>
