<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / International Company News: French market watchdog in
Eurotunnel inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Commission des Operations de Bourse, the French market watchdog,
yesterday launched an official inquiry into whether Eurotunnel, the Channel
tunnel operator, fairly presented its financial position in its rights issue
prospectus published in May this year.
In a letter sent to Mr Patrick Ponsolle, a Eurotunnel director, and released
late last night, the COB said it was particularly concerned about the
validity of the projections given in the document and the reasons why the
company did not report sooner on the financial impact of its delays.
The inquiry was triggered by remarks earlier this month by Mr Graham
Corbett, Eurotunnel's chief financial officer, who was reported as saying
the group had 'no hope' of meeting its profit forecasts made in May.
The release of the letter looked set to trigger a row between the COB and
Eurotunnel, which last night said it was 'surprised' by the inquiry and
'shocked' that the watchdog had made its contents public.
It may also cause a further fall today in the price of Eurotunnel's shares,
which dropped sharply after reports of Mr Corbett's comment and have been
trading at historic lows in the past few weeks with the release of
successive pieces of bad news.
The COB also raised concerns about the way in which Mr Corbett communicated
his doubts through the press rather than by an official statement, which it
said was more serious given that Eurotunnel is quoted in both London and
Paris.
Eurotunnel said it would co-operate fully with the COB, but stressed that
the projections given in the prospectus were always illustrative and subject
to change.
'We don't believe we have improperly provided any information,' it said. 'If
the assumptions have changed, it's not unreasonable that the projections
have changed.'
</TEXT>
