<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / P&amp;G sues bank over big loss on derivatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Procter &amp; Gamble has filed a lawsuit against Bankers Trust seeking damages
of more than Dollars 130m (Pounds 80m) over a derivative contract that
caused a big loss at the US consumer products giant. The legal action is the
second against the bank over losses stemming from derivatives.
In its lawsuit, P&amp;G claimed the bank did not 'accurately and fully' disclose
information about the derivatives contract. It is claiming Dollars 130m in
compensatory damages, and an unspecified amount of punitive damages.
'Bankers Trust called themselves the experts and encouraged Procter &amp; Gamble
to enter into a transaction we never would have accepted had it been fully
and accurately presented,' Mr Edwin Artzt, chairman, said.
He added: 'There is a notion that end users of derivatives must be held
accountable for what they buy. We agree completely, but only if the terms
and risks are fully and accurately disclosed.'
The most successful and ambitious of the US banks in the derivatives sector
before the turmoil that hit markets earlier this year, Bankers Trust was
sued last month by Gibson Greetings over losses of Dollars 20m it sustained
on derivatives bought from the bank. Derivatives are instruments whose value
is at least partly based on some underlying asset or market.
The P&amp;G suit stems from an interest rate swap contract, under which P&amp;G and
the bank had agreed to exchange payments in the future based on the interest
rates prevailing at the time. The scale of the payments made by each side
would be based on the difference between the yield on five-year and 30-year
US government bond.
Bankers Trust retorted that its actions had been 'legal, proper and
appropriate', adding that P&amp;G knowingly took a risk on the direction of US
interest rates, after extensive discussions between the two sides about the
risks involved.
P&amp;G maintains it entered the contract as part of its normal practice of
using derivatives to reduce exposure to interest-rate changes. The value of
the contract plummeted in early February, when US interest rates were
increased for the first time in four years. P&amp;G terminated the transaction,
leading in part to after-tax losses of Dollars 102m it reported in April.
</TEXT>
