<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Westminster council made house repairs worth Pounds 12m 'for
free'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Westminster City Council has failed to charge its leaseholders for Pounds
12m of repair costs since 1988, the Chartered Institute of Public Finance
and Accountancy claims in its journal Public Finance today.
People who bought their properties either under the Tories' right-to-buy
legislation or as part of the council's controversial designated sales
policy, currently under investigation by the district auditor, had major
repair work carried out for free.
The council said it had instigated its own investigation into the backlog of
charges and was seeking legal advice. It said: 'There have been concerns
over procedure. It may be that the report highlights inefficiency.'
Labour councillors claimed yesterday that the council had been guilty of
'appalling negligence and incompetence' and suggested that the officers
responsible could be liable to be surcharged.
Ms Jill Selbourne, who speaks for the Labour group on housing, told Public
Finance: 'The housing revenue account, that is the tenants, are paying for
all this scandalous behaviour (the failure to charge for repairs earlier).
This is surchargeable. Somebody, somewhere, is responsible for this via
negligence.'
Cipfa's journal says the surcharge could be as much as Pounds 22m, once lost
interest on the charges which should have been collected is taken into
account.
However, Labour councillors did not claim yesterday that there is any link
with the alleged use of the designated sales policy to 'gerrymander' the
council's housing stock by selling properties in electorally marginal wards
to potential Tory voters.
Westminster also emphatically denied any links with alleged gerrymandering,
saying: 'This is not the result of a corrupt policy.'
Mr Bill Roots, the council's chief executive, told Public Finance: 'We have
a major issue which goes back a number of years. We have taken copious legal
advice on what we can do.
'We have tried to weigh up the council's responsibilities and roles to
lessees as opposed to its wider responsibilities.'
Mr John Magill, the district auditor leading the investigation into the
'homes for votes' allegations, has qualified the council's accounts for
1993-94. He told the journal: 'Preliminary findings suggest that there has
been a significant under-recovery of costs over several years.'
Ms Selbourne adds in the journal that the council's legal advice on whether
the charges could be recovered from leaseholders was 'contradictory'. The
consensus of five legal opinions sought by the council indicated that it
would only be able to recover 18 months of charges, she said.
Mr Peter Bradley, another Labour councillor, said yesterday the backlog in
charges would be a 'major shock' to leaseholders, who now faced 'enormous
bills' of up to Pounds 20,000.
He said one leaseholder in his ward had already been 'presented with a bill
for Pounds 12,000', which she could not afford.
</TEXT>
