<HEADLINE>
FT  28 OCT 94 / Cost of library to be announced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Firm projections of the costs of the new British library and its completion
date will be announced before the Budget, the Department of National
Heritage said yesterday.
Controversial sprinkler and cabling provisions will also be announced.
In July the Commons national heritage committee described the new library,
near London's St Pancras station, as 'one of the ugliest buildings in the
world' and said costs had increased to Pounds 450m from an original estimate
of Pounds 116m.
The National Audit Office, the public spending watchdog, is due to
investigate the delays and expense involved.
Yesterday the department confirmed that Mr Richard Pardey, the project
manager brought in from the private sector to oversee the building seven
years ago, was moving to a new position, liaising with the office's
investigation.
It said Mr Pardey was 'uniquely well-placed to be in charge of our
response'. His contract ends next year, and the department said his
successor would have a reasonable amount of time to do the job.
</TEXT>
